03767nam a2200553Ia 9781927356180DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a9781927356180  a(DE-B1597)665454  a(OCoLC)848150008  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBF311 D272 2013 7aSCI0900002bisacsh04a1531 aDawson, Michael R. W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMind, Body, World :bFoundations of Cognitive Science /cMichael R. W. Dawson. 1aEdmonton, Alberta : bAthabasca University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (506 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOPEL: Open Paths to Enriched Learning00tFrontmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCognitive science arose in the 1950s when it became apparent that a number of disciplines, including psychology, computer science, linguistics, and philosophy, were fragmenting. Perhaps owing to the field’s immediate origins in cybernetics, as well as to the foundational assumption that cognition is information processing, cognitive science initially seemed more unified than psychology. However, as a result of differing interpretations of the foundational assumption and dramatically divergent views of the meaning of the term information processing, three separate schools emerged: classical cognitive science, connectionist cognitive science, and embodied cognitive science. Examples, cases, and research findings taken from the wide range of phenomena studied by cognitive scientists effectively explain and explore the relationship among the three perspectives. Intended to introduce both graduate and senior undergraduate students to the foundations of cognitive science, Mind, Body, World addresses a number of questions currently being asked by those practicing in the field: What are the core assumptions of the three different schools? What are the relationships between these different sets of core assumptions? Is there only one cognitive science, or are there many different cognitive sciences? Giving the schools equal treatment and displaying a broad and deep understanding of the field, Dawson highlights the fundamental tensions and lines of fragmentation that exist among the schools and provides a refreshing and unifying framework for students of cognitive science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCognitive science. 7aSCIENCE / Cognitive Science.2bisacsh  aclassical cognitive science.  aconnectivist.  aembodied.  apsychology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781927356180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781927356180/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles